---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Masson & Parker (2026) - Calibrating Galaxy Infall Times - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Calibrating Galaxy Infall Times in Groups and Clusters with IllustrisTNG Simulations</h1>
        
        <div class="paper-meta">
            <p><strong>Authors:</strong> Florine Masson, Laura C. Parker</p>
            <p><strong>arXiv ID:</strong> <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.13010" target="_blank">2603.13010</a></p>
            <p><strong>Date:</strong> 2026-03-13</p>
            <p><strong>Status:</strong> Accepted for publication in ApJ</p>
            <p><strong>DOI:</strong> <a href="https://doi.org/10.3847/1538-4357/ae4e21">10.3847/1538-4357/ae4e21</a></p>
        </div>

        <div class="abstract-box">
            <h3>Abstract</h3>
            <p>The time since a galaxy first became a satellite is central to understanding how environment drives <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_evolution" text="galaxy evolution" />, yet it cannot be measured directly. Using the TNG300 and TNG-Cluster simulations, the authors track satellites from z=1 to z=0 and derive a simple, redshift-dependent prescription for T<sub>inf</sub> based on position in <WikiLink slug="pages/projected_phase_space" text="projected phase space" /> and stellar mass, via symbolic regression. The resulting calibration provides continuous, observation-ready estimates of <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="infall time" /> across projected phase space. The T<sub>inf</sub> distribution is often well described by two components, and analytic expressions are provided for the corresponding characteristic timescales<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-0">Key Findings</h2>

        <h3>Continuous Infall-Time Formula (Eq. 8)</h3>
        <p>The central result is an analytic, redshift-dependent calibration of <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="galaxy infall time" /> T<sub>inf</sub> as a function of projected phase-space position (r, v) and stellar mass M<sub>*</sub> (Section IV.1.1, Eq. 3/8)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>:</p>
        <p class="equation"><code>T_inf / 1 Gyr = max(0, -v + [A(z) - log10(M*/10^10 Msun)] / [B(z) + r^C(z)])</code></p>
        <ul>
            <li>This functional form was discovered via the PySR symbolic regression package (Cranmer, 2023)<sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup>, searching over monotonic operators to avoid overfitting (Section IV.1)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>The formula is continuous across <WikiLink slug="pages/projected_phase_space" text="projected phase space" />, eliminating edge effects from previous discrete-zone methods such as Pasquali et al. (2019)<sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup> and Rhee et al. (2017)<sup><a href="#ref4">4</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Halo Mass Independence</h3>
        <p>Host <WikiLink slug="pages/dark_matter_halos" text="halo mass" /> M<sub>h</sub> was tested as a predictor but found to have negligible predictive power beyond (r, v, M<sub>*</sub>) (Section IV.1)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. This confirms earlier findings by Pasquali et al. (2019)<sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup> and Rhee et al. (2017)<sup><a href="#ref4">4</a></sup> that halo mass dependencies are weak.</p>

        <h3>Redshift Evolution (z = 0 to z = 1)</h3>
        <p>The coefficients A, B, C evolve with redshift (Section IV.2, Eqs. 4-6)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><code>A(z) = 8.384z^2 - 14.603z + 14.758</code></li>
            <li><code>B(z) = 0.694z^2 - 0.001z + 1.613</code></li>
            <li><code>C(z) = 0.704z + 1.347</code></li>
        </ul>
        <p>Using z=0 coefficients at higher redshift systematically increases the RMSE, underscoring the importance of redshift-dependent calibration (Section IV.2, Fig. 7)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</p>

        <h3>Prediction Uncertainty</h3>
        <p>The overall RMSE at z=0 is 2.31 Gyr for individual galaxies (Section IV.1.2)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. RMSE decreases to ~1 Gyr at z=1 due to shorter available cosmic time (Section IV.2, Eq. 7)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>:</p>
        <p class="equation"><code>RMSE(z) / 1 Gyr = 1.328z^2 - 2.737z + 2.281</code></p>

        <h3>Bimodal Infall-Time Distributions</h3>
        <p>At most <WikiLink slug="pages/projected_phase_space" text="projected phase-space" /> locations, the T<sub>inf</sub> distribution is bimodal rather than unimodal, consistent with findings by Dou and Yu (2025)<sup><a href="#ref5">5</a></sup>. The authors model these as two Gaussian components representing early- and late-infall populations (Section VI)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Analytic expressions for the two Gaussian means are derived via symbolic regression (Section VI.2, Eqs. 10-11)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>:
                <ul>
                    <li><code>T_mean,1 = (3.981 - r)^2.272 / [v + sqrt(log10(M*/Msun))]</code> Gyr</li>
                    <li><code>T_mean,2 = -4.723*sqrt(r) - v - log10(M*/Msun) + 22.283</code> Gyr</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>RMSE of these component means: 0.56 Gyr and 1.20 Gyr respectively (Section VI.2)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>The standard deviations and relative weights of the two components could not be reliably parameterized, suggesting additional physical parameters beyond (r, v, M<sub>*</sub>) are needed (Section VI.3)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Infall Definition at 3R200</h3>
        <p>Infall is defined as first crossing of 3R<sub>200</sub> rather than R<sub>200</sub>, for two reasons (Section III.1)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Environmental effects (e.g., <WikiLink slug="pages/ram_pressure_stripping" text="ram-pressure stripping" />, tidal forces) are known to influence galaxies beyond R<sub>200</sub>, citing Balogh et al. (2000)<sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup>, Oman et al. (2020)<sup><a href="#ref7">7</a></sup>, and Haines et al. (2015)<sup><a href="#ref8">8</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>Using R<sub>200</sub> introduces an artificial discontinuity in the T<sub>inf</sub> distribution at r=1 in PPS (Section III.3, Fig. 2)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Interloper Contamination</h3>
        <p>Projection effects contaminate PPS with galaxies at true 3D distances &gt; 3R<sub>200</sub>. Interloper fractions exceed 60% at large radii (r &gt; 2) and high velocities, but fall below 10% at r &lt; 1 (Section III.4, Fig. 3)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. The authors recommend restricting observational analyses to r &lt; 2, following Rhee et al. (2017)<sup><a href="#ref4">4</a></sup> and Dou and Yu (2025)<sup><a href="#ref5">5</a></sup>.</p>

        <h2 id="section-1">Data and Methods</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Simulations:</strong> TNG300 (large-volume, (302.6 Mpc)^3) and TNG-Cluster (352 zoom-in cluster re-simulations), both from the IllustrisTNG suite with matched resolution (m_baryon ~ 1.1e7 Msun) (Section II.1)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li><strong>Sample:</strong> &gt;1.5 million galaxies with M<sub>*</sub> &gt; 10^9 Msun in halos with M<sub>h</sub> &gt; 10^13 Msun, within 3R<sub>200</sub> of host center. Three LOS projections used for statistics (Section II.1.1)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li><strong>Galaxy tracking:</strong> SubLink merger trees trace normalized group-centric distance R_3D/R<sub>200</sub> backward in time; earliest snapshot below 3 defines infall redshift (Section III.2)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li><strong>Velocity dispersion:</strong> Halo sigma computed following Yang et al. (2007) as sigma = 397.9 km/s * (M_h / 10^14 h^-1 Msun)^0.3214 (Section III.3, Eq. 1)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref9">9</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-2">Comparison to Previous Work</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Pasquali et al. (2019)</strong><sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup>: Divided PPS into 8 discrete zones out to R<sub>200</sub> with infall defined at R<sub>200</sub> crossing. Mean T<sub>inf</sub> progression across zones matches well; systematic offset of 2.3-3.3 Gyr reflects the different infall radius definition. RMSE values are comparable (Section V.1, Table 1)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li><strong>Rhee et al. (2017)</strong><sup><a href="#ref4">4</a></sup>: Also used discrete PPS zones. This work extends their approach by providing a continuous formula and incorporating stellar mass and redshift dependence<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li><strong>Dou and Yu (2025)</strong><sup><a href="#ref5">5</a></sup>: Demonstrated T<sub>inf</sub> bimodality in PPS regions. This work confirms and extends their finding by providing analytic expressions for the two Gaussian component means (Section VI)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-3">Related Concepts</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/projected_phase_space" text="Projected Phase Space" /> - Core observable used in this calibration</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="Galaxy Infall Time" /> - The quantity being calibrated</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/environmental_quenching" text="Environmental Quenching" /> - Motivation: infall time constrains environmental processing timescales</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/ram_pressure_stripping" text="Ram Pressure Stripping" /> - Environmental mechanism operating beyond R<sub>200</sub></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_clusters" text="Galaxy Clusters" /> - Host environments studied</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_groups" text="Galaxy Groups" /> - Host environments studied</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/dark_matter_halos" text="Dark Matter Halos" /> - Halo mass tested as predictor (found negligible)</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/preprocessing" text="Preprocessing" /> - Environmental effects at large cluster-centric radii</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_bimodality" text="Galaxy Bimodality" /> - Broader context of environmental galaxy transformation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-4">Significance</h2>
        <p>This paper provides the first continuous, redshift-dependent, observation-ready calibration of galaxy infall time in projected phase space. The key advances over prior work (Pasquali et al. 2019<sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup>; Rhee et al. 2017<sup><a href="#ref4">4</a></sup>) are<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Continuous functional form eliminates edge effects at zone boundaries.</li>
            <li>Explicit incorporation of stellar mass and redshift dependence (0 &lt; z &lt; 1).</li>
            <li>Characterization of T<sub>inf</sub> bimodality with analytic Gaussian component means.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>However, the intrinsic scatter remains large (~2.3 Gyr at z=0), and the variables (r, v, M<sub>*</sub>) are insufficient to determine which of the two infall-time components applies to a given galaxy. Identifying additional distinguishing parameters is flagged as the key open problem (Section VI.4)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</p>

